#----------------------------------------------
# import RC files and compile into a dataframe
#----------------------------------------------
setName <- paste("Set", 1:length(rnapc_data_dir))
date <- c("2015-07-03", "2015-07-03", "2015-07-03")
DatList <- list()
for (h in 1:length(rnapc_data_dir)) {
    files <- list.files(rnapc_data_dir[h], full.names = TRUE)
    dat <- lapply(as.list(files), function(i) {
        rccToDat(fileName = i)
    }) %>% do.call(rbind, .)
    dat$Set <- setName[h]
    dat$Date <- date[h]
    DatList[[h]] <- dat
}
Dat <- do.call(rbind, DatList)
## Fix gene Names for some genes
Dat$Name[Dat$Accession == "NM_014512.1"] <- "KIR2DS1"  ## KIR_Activating_Subgroup_2
Dat$Name[Dat$Accession == "NM_014218.2"] <- "KIR2DL1"  ## KIR_Inhibiting_Subgroup_1
Dat$Name[Dat$Accession == "NM_001083539.1"] <- "KIR3DS1"  ## KIR_Activating_Subgroup_1
Dat$Name[Dat$Accession == "NM_014511.3"] <- "KIR2DL3"  ## KIR_Inhibiting_Subgroup_2
Dat$Name[Dat$Name == "IL8"] <- "CXCL8"
write.csv(Dat, rnapc_raw_dir)

3 2) Quality Control / Quality Assessment

3.1 2a. Fields of View (FOV)

  • each lane is imaged in discrete units called FOVs
  • FOV Count = # of FOVs for which imaging was attempted
  • FOV Counted = # of FOVs sucessfully imaged
  • Causes of discrepancy between FOV Count & FOV Counted: optical issues such as bubbles or insufficient oiling of cartridge
  • Imaging QC (nSolver default): Flag lanes when percent FOV registration is less than 75

3.2 2b. Binding Density

  • the Digital analyzer does not count codes that overlap
  • if too many codes overlap, there can be significant data loss
  • Binding densitiy (image saturation) = measure of the # of optical features per square micron
  • binding density > 2: significant numbers of codes ignored, affects quantification and linearity of the assay
  • Binding Density QC (nSolver default): Flag lanes when binding density is outside of 0.005-2.25 range
qc <- data %>% mutate(FOVratio = FovCounted_Lane_Attributes/FovCount_Lane_Attributes) %>% 
    dplyr::select(FOVratio, BindingDensity = BindingDensity_Lane_Attributes, 
        Sample, Set, ID_Lane_Attributes) %>% gather(QCVar, QCmetrics, -c(Sample, 
    Set, ID_Lane_Attributes)) %>% group_by(Sample, QCVar, Set) %>% # distinct(Sample, Set, ID_Lane_Attributes) %>%
mutate(Sample_Lane = paste(Sample, ID_Lane_Attributes, sep = "_"))
qc$Sample_Lane <- factor(qc$Sample_Lane, levels = unique(qc$Sample_Lane))

qc %>% ungroup %>% dplyr::group_by(QCVar) %>% dplyr::summarise(min = min(QCmetrics), 
    max = max(QCmetrics))

3.3 2c. Internal Controls

  • nanoString uses External RNA Control Consortium (ERCC) controls for both positive and negative controls
  • ERRC is a group that develops RNA transcripts not homologous to known organisms, generate consistent results in gene expression data –> used to assess technical performance in gene expression assays.

3.3.1 2d. Positive Controls

  • For each sample, there are six positive controls (POS_A-POS_F) corresponding to six different concentrations in the 30 ul hybridzation: 128fM, 32fM, 8fM, 2fM, 0.5fM, and 0.125fM.
  • Positive Control Linearity QC: Flag lanes when Positive Control \(R^2\) value is less than 0.9
posConc <- c(128, 32, 8, 2, 0.5, 0.125)
names(posConc) <- paste0(paste("POS", LETTERS[1:6], sep = "_"), paste0("(", 
    posConc, ")"))
posDat <- data %>% filter(CodeClass == "Positive_Code_Summary") %>% mutate(posConc = posConc[as.character(Name)], 
    Sample_Lane = paste(Sample, ID_Lane_Attributes, sep = "_"))

mods <- posDat %>% group_by(ID_Lane_Attributes, Set) %>% do(., r2 = summary(lm(Count ~ 
    posConc, data = .))$r.squared)
r.squared <- data.frame(ID_Lane_Attributes = mods$ID_Lane_Attributes, R2 = round(unlist(mods$r2), 
    2), Set = mods$Set)
r.squared$x <- 20
r.squared$y <- 100

all(mods$r2 > 0.99)
## [1] TRUE
## order E samples from 1-36
posDat$Sample_Lane <- factor(posDat$Sample_Lane, levels = unique(posDat$Sample_Lane))

3.3.2 2e. Negative Controls

  • estimate systemic background counts within any single hybridization reaction.
  • Positive Control Limit of Detection QC: Flag lanes when 0.5fM positive control is less than or equal to 2 standard deviations above the mean of the negative controls.
negSD <- data %>% dplyr::filter(CodeClass == "Negative_Code_Summary") %>% group_by(fileName, 
    Set, Sample) %>% dplyr::summarise(negThres = mean(Count) + 2 * sd(Count))
pos0.5 = posDat %>% filter(posConc == 0.5)
all(levels(negSD$Sample) == levels(pos0.5$Sample))  # TRUE
## [1] TRUE
negPos <- as.data.frame(rbind(negSD[, c("Sample", "Set", "negThres")], setNames(pos0.5[, 
    c("Sample", "Set", "Count")], c("Sample", "Set", "negThres"))))
negPos$Type = rep(c("Neg(Mean+2SD)", "Pos0.5fM"), each = nrow(negSD))
negPos$Sample <- factor(negPos$Sample, levels = unique(negPos$Sample)[order(as.numeric(gsub("E", 
    "", unique(negPos$Sample))))])

ggplot(negPos, aes(x = Sample, y = negThres, color = Type)) + geom_point() + 
    ylab("Count") + customTheme(sizeStripFont = 15, xAngle = 30, hjust = 1, 
    vjust = 1, xSize = 8, ySize = 10, xAxisSize = 10, yAxisSize = 10) + facet_grid(Set ~ 
    .)

4 3) Normalization

4.1 3a. Positive Control Normalization

  • Positive controls normalize all platform associated sources of variation (e.g. automated purfication, hybridization conditions etc.)
  • does not account for sample input between technical and biological replicates
  • Positive Control Scaling factor QC: If the positive control scaling factor is outside a range of 0.3-3, –> may indicate significant under-performance of a lane
# str(posDat)

posNF <- posDat %>% group_by(Sample) %>% dplyr::summarise(posGeoMean = geometric.mean(Count), 
    fileName = unique(fileName)) %>% mutate(posNF = mean(posGeoMean)/posGeoMean)
range(posNF$posNF)
## [1] 0.8437908 1.2326545
all(posNF$posNF < 3 & posNF$posNF > 0.3)
## [1] TRUE
dataNorm <- full_join(data, posNF, by = "fileName") %>% mutate(posNorm = Count * 
    posNF)

# check if the sum of the positive controls is the same for each assay
dataNorm %>% group_by(fileName) %>% filter(CodeClass == "Positive_Code_Summary") %>% 
    dplyr::summarise(sumPosSample = geometric.mean(posNorm), Sample = unique(Sample.x), 
        Set = unique(Set)) %>% dplyr::select(Sample, sumPosSample) %>% ggplot(aes(x = Sample, 
    y = sumPosSample)) + geom_point() + theme_bw() + ylab("Positive Normalization Factor")

cvList <- list()
for (i in 3:13) {
    genes <- as.character(res.BM$ranking[1:i])
    
    ## House-keeping normalization factor
    hkNF <- dataNorm3 %>% filter(Name %in% genes) %>% group_by(Sample.x) %>% 
        dplyr::summarise(hkGeoMean = geometric.mean(posNorm)) %>% mutate(hkNF = mean(hkGeoMean)/hkGeoMean)
    
    ## normalize data
    hkNorm <- full_join(dataNorm3, hkNF, by = "Sample.x") %>% mutate(hkNorm = posNorm * 
        hkNF)
    
    ## calculate CVs
    cvDat <- hkNorm %>% filter(CodeClass == "Endogenous_Code_Summary") %>% group_by(Name) %>% 
        dplyr::summarise(cv = sd(hkNorm)/mean(hkNorm))
    cv <- cvDat$cv
    names(cv) <- cvDat$Name
    cvList[[i - 2]] <- cv
}
names(cvList) <- paste0("hk", "1-", 3:13)

## cvs of raw data calculate CVs
cvDat <- dataNorm3 %>% filter(CodeClass == "Endogenous_Code_Summary") %>% group_by(Name) %>% 
    dplyr::summarise(cv = sd(posNorm)/mean(posNorm))
cv <- cvDat$cv
names(cv) <- cvDat$Name
cvList$hk0 <- cv

## total sum normalization total sum normalization factor
totalNF <- dataNormEndoFiltered %>% group_by(Sample.x) %>% dplyr::summarise(totalsumMean = sum(posNorm)) %>% 
    mutate(totalsumNF = mean(totalsumMean)/totalsumMean)
## normalize data
totalNorm <- full_join(dataNormEndoFiltered, totalNF, by = "Sample.x") %>% mutate(totalNorm = posNorm * 
    totalsumNF)

# ## ttm normalization mdge = DGEList(counts=m1, group=group) # ttm
# normalization m2 = calcNormFactors(mdge)


## calculate CVs
cvDat <- totalNorm %>% filter(CodeClass == "Endogenous_Code_Summary") %>% group_by(Name) %>% 
    dplyr::summarise(cv = sd(totalNorm)/mean(totalNorm))
cv <- cvDat$cv
names(cv) <- cvDat$Name
cvList$total <- cv

## boxplot of CVs for various normalizations
boxplot(do.call(cbind, cvList), ylab = "coefficient of variation")

## histogram of CVs for various normalizations
do.call(cbind, cvList) %>% as.data.frame %>% gather(hkComb, cv) %>% ggplot(aes(x = cv, 
    color = hkComb)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5)

5 4) Differential Expression Analysis: ERvsDR after total sum normalization (since this normalized had the lowest mean cv compared to the hk normalizations

genEset0 <- totalNorm %>% filter(CodeClass == "Endogenous_Code_Summary") %>% 
    dplyr::select(Sample.x, Name, totalNorm) %>% spread(Sample.x, totalNorm)
genEset <- log2(as.matrix(genEset0[, -1]))
genEset[genEset < 0] <- 0
rownames(genEset) <- genEset0$Name

demoPre <- demoPre[colnames(genEset), ]
all(demoPre$EorV_number == colnames(genEset))
## [1] TRUE
table(demoPre$calculated_Response, demoPre$givenResponse)
##     
##      DR ER
##   DR 20  0
##   ER  0 15
## differential expression analysis
design <- model.matrix(~factor(demoPre$calculated_Response, levels = c("ER", 
    "DR")))
fit <- eBayes(lmFit(genEset, design, method = "ls"))
top.total <- topTable(fit, coef = 2, adjust.method = "BH", n = nrow(fit))
length(top.total$logFC[top.total$P.Value < 0.05])
## [1] 50
plot(-log10(top.total$P.Value) ~ top.total$logFC)
abline(h = -log10(0.05), lty = 2, col = 2)
